<font color="#FF0000">REPLY</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec  1 15:17:26 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
I appreciate the incredible dilemma that young men who were drafted into the war faced and I hate what happened to them as a result of the war.  Yet Americans have a responsibility to citizenship and to participate in the making of foreign policy.  This can be learned in any junior high civics class.  Although at any one time a government (which is not something etherial but a concrete group of people) would like its citizens to obey draft orders without question, it is vital to a democracy that citizens be involved in making those decisions to draft and not to draft, and to go or not to go when called.  What would have happened if George Washington or Thomas Jefferson or Abraham Lincoln had simply taken the easy positions of obeying England or not abolishing slavery.  I think everyone recognizes that there are times that one must not obey government or take the easy path.  Those who went to Vietnam because they couldn't get enough information on it in their rural communities were not paying attention to the world around them and the ways in which things happening in Vietnam could mean the loss of life in Rochester, Minnesota (for example).  We cannot shirk those responsibilities of active involvement and reflection, which can either prevent us from fighting or compell us to battle.  Some things are worth fighting for; communism in Vietnam was not our thing to fight against.  With the fall of communism around the world, Americans who lost loved ones are asking what the carnage was for.
<p><code>-- cyberspace  (Lear S. Parson) </code><p>


